<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> Current practice is to use <i>c</i><sub>0</sub> to denote the speed of light in vacuum according to <a href="/wiki/ISO_31" title="ISO 31">ISO 31</a>. In the original Recommendation of 1983, the symbol <i>c</i> was used for this purpose. See <a href="http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP330/sp330.pdf" class="external text" title="http://physics.nist.gov/Pubs/SP330/sp330.pdf" rel="nofollow">NIST <i>Special Publication 330</i>, Appendix 2, p. 45</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.zpenergy.com/downloads/Maxwell_1864_4.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.zpenergy.com/downloads/Maxwell_1864_4.pdf" rel="nofollow">Maxwell 1864 4</a> (page 497 of the article and page 9 of the pdf link)</li>
